text: Of course. Thanks, Corey. Also from my side, as you might've already figured out, we call ourselves the two quants and Moritz is clearly the talking quant, so I'm the Moritz, the coding quant, I'm not the one that tells my wife over lunch that I'm dealing with models, she knows that, she knows the dumb jokes and everything around that. So basically how did I get into this? How did I meet the other Moritz? I think that is the journey. It all started for me when I started math finance, I did a PhD in statistics afterwards. Finished my academic studies around the time when the financial crisis hit. So not the best time to get into the market. So I decided to do the PhD. Did that on volatility modeling, AI learning models, prediction, multidimensional vol modeling. So everything at quant nowadays does. So also not definitely in the direction of portfolio management, maybe, but I decided to start out in quant asset management, joined a asset manager in Germany here. As a portfolio manager and that's where I actually met Moritz. Then it was not two quants, so we were named Moritz and Moritz, but we didn't start the two quants back then. It was confusing for anyone around. We decided to split up again, get our separate ways. So I went to Munich to Scalable Capital, which is one of the digital asset managers in Europe, one of the largest ones, managed around 2 billion in 50,000 accounts there. Everything high-end. It was highly automated, but straightforward ETF portfolios back in the day. I then reunited with Moritz at Munich Reinvestment Partners, which is an internal hedge fund or fund at Munich Re, which now focuses on sustainable investments. And during that time, exactly in 2020, we decided to launch two quants as a kind of research site, a blog. And we did that since then, even though our ways kind of led us away from Munich Reinvestment Partners. We are both now working for Real Vision. We are also working for Xpem, the exponential age asset management company. So that's where we are reunited again. So our paths, they separate and they cross back again.
